  "method": "1) Define and elicit the capability. Curate a compact, capability-specific evaluation set with paired counterfactuals that selectively disrupt the target behavior while holding other factors constant (e.g., prompts that require subject–verb agreement vs minimally-edited distractors that remove the need for agreement). Fix an external scoring function that reflects the capability (task accuracy, calibrated reference metrics, or human ratings), and lock an execution protocol (temperature, seeds) to reduce evaluation noise. Run clean and corrupted inputs through the frozen model to produce activation traces per component (e.g., attention heads, MLP neurons, or low-rank feature directions).\n\n2) Fast screening to localize candidates. Perform lightweight, layer- and component-wise screening to reduce the search space: train linear probes on intermediate representations to decode a capability-relevant target (e.g., the next correct token among distractors) and compute per-component decodability and mutual-information gains. Combine with coarse behavioral importance (e.g., masking a head group and measuring accuracy drop) to form a shortlist of candidate components per layer. Keep this stage deliberately permissive to favor recall over precision.\n\n3) Causal subnetwork discovery via sparse, differentiable masking. Parameterize a binary mask over component groups (e.g., heads/MLP blocks) with per-layer group sparsity and a small, learnable controller that samples masks (e.g., Bernoulli or Gumbel–Softmax) during training. Optimize the mask with a two-contrast objective: (a) with only the masked-on components allowed to transmit their activations (others zeroed or bypassed), the model should retain high capability score on the clean set; (b) when the same components are ablated (masked off) in the full model, the capability score should drop sharply on the same inputs and their counterfactuals. Add group-L0/L1 penalties and a hierarchical per-layer budget to encourage minimal, structured solutions. For efficiency and stability, estimate gradients of the discrete mask with sampling-based estimators and restrict forward/backward to the expanded subgraph touched by sampled components. Iterate mask training only over the shortlisted candidates from step 2.\n\n4) Causal verification and actionable editing. Verify the discovered set by do-style interventions: (i) ablate-only tests (turn off the set and confirm capability loss), (ii) rescue tests (enable only the set and confirm capability recovery on counterfactual-disrupted inputs), and (iii) activation patching (swap clean vs corrupted activations at candidate sites and measure output deltas) to quantify average causal effect. For interpretation, output the minimal causal circuit (components and their strongest edges/IO tokens) with effect sizes. For editing, use the mask as a handle: suppress a capability by zeroing/scaling its components; amplify by gain-scaling or targeted fine-tuning restricted to the set; or transplant by copying the set (and their layer-normalization context) into a sibling model and validating transfer. Always re-check collateral effects on unrelated control tasks to bound side effects.",
  "rationale": "The pipeline turns correlational signals into causal evidence by pairing a permissive, high-recall screen (linear probes and coarse ablations) with targeted do-interventions on a sparsified set of components. Learning a minimal masked subnetwork that both preserves the capability when kept and erases it when removed operationalizes causal necessity and sufficiency, while hierarchical group sparsity enforces component-level structure and parsimony. Sampling-based mask optimization makes the discrete selection tractable without exhaustively testing all component combinations.\n\nThe verification suite (ablate, rescue, and activation patching) provides convergent evidence that the selected components implement the capability, and the learned mask becomes a practical control for editing—allowing suppression, amplification, or transfer—while external, reference-grounded evaluation avoids over-trusting the model’s own internal signals.",
